    <segment id="1" parent="30" relname="span">
Participants on this list have raised a classic chicken-and-egg question:</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="elaboration">
which comes first? </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="30" relname="elaboration"> How do we get scientists involved in what we&apos;re doing?</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="30" relname="elaboration">
Do we have anything useful to contribute to what they&apos;re doing anyway?</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="34" relname="span">   
My associates and I addressed these issues in our gently satirical &quot;Hard
Program&quot; manifesto in _Social Epistemology_ 1992, # 3.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="33" relname="span">  We argue for 
using what scientists say about themselves as &quot;prima facie&quot; evidence for
judging the adequacy of our interpretations -- with the prima facie 
strongly emphasized.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="9" relname="antithesis">  The existence of disagreement should not lead to 
automatic rejection of our interpretation,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="32" relname="span"> so much as point to a problem
that needs to be addressed. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="10" relname="condition"> If science studies &quot;brings the scientist
back in&quot; in the way that we describe,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="35" relname="span"> then the field may very well have
important contributions to make in the form of how research is carried out,
organized, and disseminated.  </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="49" relname="span">

Which raises the question: </segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="36" relname="span"> HOw to get the ball rolling? </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="50" relname="span"> Here, I don&apos;t 
think that we lack models.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="37" relname="span">  The professional ethics community has been
very successful at getting practitioners involved in what they&apos;re doing.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="14" relname="nonvolitional-cause">
One reason has been the pressure of scandals, lawsuits, etc.</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="37" relname="elaboration"> Physicians
and surgeons turned to ethicists in the heat of the abortion debates, 
scandals over research on human subjects, and so on. </segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="39" relname="span"> We should look 
upon the SSC fiasco as an opportunity</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="17" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> -- scientists will turn to us when
they feel like they&apos;re in trouble.</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="44" relname="span">  The other important consideration of 
course is money.</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="40" relname="span">  There&apos;s money in ethics today.</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="20" relname="evidence">  One can get grants
to hold workshops and attract practioners with stipends and honoraria.</segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="41" relname="span">
Although scientists may not be as bad as lawyers</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="22" relname="circumstance"> when it comes to the
ticking meter,</segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="42" relname="span"> nevertheless they know they can be earning consulting 
fees while they are talking to us.</segment>
    <segment id="25" parent="47" relname="span">

On a different matter, I&apos;m not sanguine about a central science clearing-
house for the US govt.</segment>
    <segment id="26" parent="45" relname="disjunction">  Maybe because we&apos;re much bigger than Holland,</segment>
    <segment id="27" parent="45" relname="disjunction"> or
maybe because I don&apos;t know where science ends and other things begin,</segment>
    <segment id="28" parent="46" relname="span"> it
strikes me as an unworkable idea. </segment>
    <segment id="29" parent="28" relname="evidence"> Do we really want one office to review
everything from proposals to study ways of increasing chicken production, to
increasing student performance in public schools, to searching for the top
quark?</segment>
